  "query": "How does the evidence for using acoustic devices to reduce human-wildlife conflict at aquaculture systems compare to their use on fishing gear?",
  "relevant_summary": "Six studies investigated the use of acoustic devices at aquaculture facilities. Four of these studies demonstrated a decrease in predation on caged salmon by grey seals, harbour seals, and South American sea lions, as well as a reduction in the number of harbour seals approaching a fish cage [2775]. However, two studies found that acoustic devices did not decrease harbour seal predation at salmon farms or affect the presence, approach distances, group sizes, or time spent around fin-fish farms by common bottlenose dolphins [2775].\n\nFive studies assessed the impact of acoustic devices on fishing vessels. One study revealed that the use of acoustic devices did not lead to a reduction in the predation of squid catches by Risso\u2019s dolphins [2815]. In terms of behavior change, one controlled study observed that common bottlenose dolphins were more likely to avoid a boat when acoustic devices were active [2815]. Another study found that killer whales were initially recorded at a greater distance from a fishing vessel when an acoustic device was in use, but these distances diminished after the first exposure [2815]. Two before-and-after studies indicated that an acoustic device on a vessel led to reduced surfacing and echolocation rates, as well as decreased time spent foraging or socializing for Indo-Pacific humpback dolphins and Australian snubfin dolphins. However, it had no impact on 8\u201310 other behaviors [2815].",
